    "clung to the boathouse rafters. You think about the living seawalls unfurling like experimental gardens in the surf, about kids planting marsh grasses on terraces you helped design."
    # [Scene: Promenade — Dusk | Golden-hour with storm clouds gathering on the horizon]
    hide cassian_rhee
    hide ariana_voss

    scene bg ch13_601bcb_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A slow, descending cello line; a distant church bell tolls once.]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Wind picking up, a faint rain beginning; wave slap has softened behind the new barriers.]
    "Narration"
    "The ceremony ends. Elder Tomas lights a small torch and passes it down the line. People speak little. There is the formal language of gratitude and the more human language of loss — whispered stories of"
    "boats that came back with nets full, of an uncle who taught knot-tying on the boathouse floor, of the way the tide kept time with the town's sleep."
    "Marin Sato: (to Elder Tomas, low) 'Did we—did we do enough?'"
    "Elder Tomas: (eyes like old maps) 'Enough is a hard word. We have done what we could. We have kept many from losing themselves to the water. Whether that is enough will be told by the years, by the children who learn these rocks as their shore.'"
    "Narration"
    "You let that settle. The town is alive in ways measured by both taxes and teas, by grants and garlands. The living seawalls will, perhaps, slow erosion and provide work. A memorial program will hold names"
    "and stories. Tideguard's funds will build new training programs. The cooperative trust will run boat-restoration workshops, in Brady's pitchforked words, 'to keep the culture breathing.'"
    "Cassian Rhee: (offering a small, genuine nod) 'This is not the end. It's a beginning that looks like a compromise. I'm willing to make it better, over time.'"
    "Marin Sato: (quiet) 'Make it honest, then. If you're right about the long view, make sure the town keeps a voice.'"
    show cassian_rhee at left:
        zoom 0.7

    cassian_rhee "That's the trust's job as much as mine. I'll sign it with my name on it."
    "Narration"
    "You look at the plaque near the promenade bench — a line of inked names, a short dedication. Your name is not on it. The boathouse's name is. The space where a centuries-old doorway used to"
    "watch the sea is now a neat curve of promenade with a bench and a planted terrace. People sit and stare out at the water as if watching a dream that was clipped."
    "Ariana Voss: (softly) 'I wish—' She doesn't finish. You understand the rest: she wishes things had been different, that another path had not required so many goodbyes."
    show marin_sato at right:
        zoom 0.7

    marin_sato "So do I."
    "Narration"
    "The night comes with rain that smells like metal and rosemary. Volunteers fold tarpaulins, children kick pebbles into runoff drains, and Elder Tomas hums an old ditty as he walks home. The town moves around the wound with small, habitual acts of care."
    "You walk the promenade slowly, hands deep in pockets, the compass at your throat a cold circle that somehow centers you. You thought the decision would liberate you — that choosing a side would make the"
    "sea of consequences easier to navigate. Instead, the signature has taught you a different lesson: that leadership tastes like salt, and the right course is often the least redeeming one."
    hide cassian_rhee
    hide marin_sato

    scene bg ch13_601bcb_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single cello bows a held note; then a slow exhale of wind.]
    "Narration"
    "You breathe, and in the breath is grief and relief braided so tightly you can hardly tell where one ends. The town did not fall. The harbor's heart beats under its engineered ribs. People have roofs"
    "and work and a place to remember what was lost. The cost is real: the boathouse, the hours, the way intimate geography — the map of where people belong — has been redrawn."
    "Ariana Voss: (finding your hand again, firmer now) 'Stay? For a little while. Help me check the kelp nurseries tomorrow.'"
    "Marin Sato: (after a beat, the right kind of tired) 'I'll stay. We'll keep planting.'"
    "Narration"
    "You do not imagine easy sunsets from here on — only the steady labor of tending. There are fences to monitor, grants to wrangle, and promises to hold to the people who trusted you. Your love"
    "is not a neat ending; it is another project, jointly tended, requiring patience, apology, and work."
    "You stand together on the promenade as the rain begins in earnest. You let the cold beads land on your face and the wind thread between you. It is not the triumph you dreamed of in your idealism; it is, instead, a working compromise that keeps lives intact."
    "You palm the compass under your shirt and make yourself a small vow: to keep the town's voice loud in the trust, to make memorials real and not just placards, to keep asking the hard questions even when the councils have grown comfortable with easy answers."
    "Narration"
    "The map of intimacy and loss is altered. The seams are visible. But the town breathes. Children will learn the new stones the way old sailors learned the stars. People will quarrel and reconcile, file complaints"
    "and bake bread, learn new trades and tell stories of the boathouse. The future here will be braided — part stewardship, part surrender — and you will live within that braid, working, loving, grieving, patching."

    scene bg ch13_601bcb_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: The strings resolve into a minor chord that lingers; then wind sounds take over.]
    "Narration"
    "You walk home with salt in your lungs and a weight in your chest that feels like the price of doing what you thought was right. It's a fall in tone because the compromise is real"
    "and imperfect; it's not a neat victory or a total defeat. It is the messy, human middle of climate and care."
    "You let yourself feel that ache fully now, so that tomorrow you can face the work with both hands steady."

